05964nam a22012375i 9781400832897DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212009nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008328977 a10.1515/97814008328972doi  a(DE-B1597)585952  a(OCoLC)1257324568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSCI0750002bisacsh04a003/.541 aWainer, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPicturing the Uncertain World :bHow to Understand, Communicate, and Control Uncertainty through Graphical Display /cHoward Wainer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b11 color illus. 14 halftones. 81 line illus. 12 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tPicturing the Uncertain World -- tPart I Introduction and Overview -- tPart II Political Issues -- tPart III Educational Testing -- tPart IV Mostly Methodological -- tPart V History -- tPart VI Epilogue -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tSource Material -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his entertaining and informative book Graphic Discovery, Howard Wainer unlocked the power of graphical display to make complex problems clear. Now he's back with Picturing the Uncertain World, a book that explores how graphs can serve as maps to guide us when the information we have is ambiguous or incomplete. Using a visually diverse sampling of graphical display, from heartrending autobiographical displays of genocide in the Kovno ghetto to the "Pie Chart of Mystery" in a New Yorker cartoon, Wainer illustrates the many ways graphs can be used--and misused--as we try to make sense of an uncertain world.Picturing the Uncertain World takes readers on an extraordinary graphical adventure, revealing how the visual communication of data offers answers to vexing questions yet also highlights the measure of uncertainty in almost everything we do. Are cancer rates higher or lower in rural communities? How can you know how much money to sock away for retirement when you don't know when you'll die? And where exactly did nineteenth-century novelists get their ideas? These are some of the fascinating questions Wainer invites readers to consider. Along the way he traces the origins and development of graphical display, from William Playfair, who pioneered the use of graphs in the eighteenth century, to instances today where the public has been misled through poorly designed graphs. We live in a world full of uncertainty, yet it is within our grasp to take its measure. Read Picturing the Uncertain World and learn how.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aAmerican Psychological Association.  aAmerican Statistical Association.  aBertillon, Alphonse.  aBertillonage.  aButterflies.  aCamemberts.  aCarnegie Corporation.  aEducational Testing Service.  aFinal Solution.  aGratz v Bollinger.  aHereditary Genius (Galton).  aHispanics.  aHolmes, Sherlock.  aLaboratoire Graphique.  aMennonites.  aNapoleon.  aNightingale Rose.  aNungester, Ron.  aOlympics.  aOpen Society Institute.  aPew Research Center.  aaccelerated life testing.  aalgorithms.  aasymptotes.  abar charts.  abinomial distribution.  acancer research.  acarcinogenic effects.  acartographers.  adanger function.  adegrees of freedom.  adistributions binomial.  aearthquakes.  aempirical functions.  aethanol.  agame theory.  ahousehold income.  aignorance.  aimmigrants.  aintelligence.  aleptokurtic distributions.  aline labels.  alogarithms.  amathematics.  amedicine.  amethodology